updating LEDs faster by directly calling updateLEDs() in the melty loop.
added [probably bad] locking.

the logic is: you increment first, then check. [ideally atomically]
you only decrement it again immediately before leaving. As there is no other call to FastLED.show() in the melty code, this code should prevent multiple executions of the code at the same time on different threads. 

> void updateLEDs() 
> {
>   static volatile int inUpdate = 0;
>   inUpdate++;
>   if( inUpdate == 1 )
>   {
>     FastLED.show();
>   }
>   inUpdate--;
> }

this is the handler which gets called every 12.5 milliseconds (80/sec)  for normal display stuff. 
previous it was just a call to FastLED.show(), which resulted in the controller crashing. it needed to be power cycled to upload a new firmware. not a fun crash.
during testing it didn't crash even with the extra calls to updateLEDs(). I waited about 20 minutes with no crash, compared to a few minutes without the lock-like code, so shipping it.

