the am32 code is not incomprehensible - you  can look to see what its doing with those settings here: https://github.com/am32-firmware/AM32/blob/main/Src/main.c
It appears to do consistency checks when reading the eeprom (likely so it doesnt immediately explode the esc if a flash goes wrong) (starting line 672)
```
        if (eepromBuffer.drag_brake_strength == 0 || eepromBuffer.drag_brake_strength > 10) { // drag brake 1-10
            eepromBuffer.drag_brake_strength = 10;
        }
```

It is not difficult to rebuild the am32 firmware and flash it to your escs if you want to try values outside that range

I think I mightve found a better way to improve braking than just blindly looking at settings. When braking, AM32 either calls `fullBrake()` or `proportionalBrake()`depending on how much braking is required.
These functions are defined on a per-MCU level, but for the MCU I am using (F421) it appears that they just short the motor wires together. 
```
void fullBrake()
{ // full braking shorting all low sides
    phaseALOW();
    phaseBLOW();
    phaseCLOW();
}
```
```
void proportionalBrake()
{ // alternate all channels between braking (ABC LOW)
    // and coasting (ABC float) put lower channel into
    // alternate mode and turn upper OFF for each
    // channel
    // turn all HIGH channels off for ABC
```
So if you want to increase braking what you might be able to do is instead actively use the battery voltage to push against the rotation of the motor.

(as for increasing the servo pwm frequency, you might be able to hack that together but just using dshot is likely an easier solution since its already built and includes checksums. you will probably lose throttle resolution as well if you try to compress the servo band - theres already a decent amount of timing jitter at 1-2ms)

There is precedent for active braking in AM32, and though it only works when stopped it does offer a noticable increase in braking torque
